Analyzing NYC Taxi and Limousine Commission (TLC)¶

The data source is obtained from NYC Taxi and Limousine Commission (TLC) website (https://www1.nyc.gov/site/tlc/about/tlc-trip-record-data.page). There are lot of data available on Yellow and Green Taxis. The data records include fields capturing pick-up and drop-off dates/times, pick-up and drop-off locations, trip distances, itemized fares, rate types, payment types, and driver-reported passenger counts. The data used in the attached datasets were collected and provided to the NYC Taxi and Limousine Commission (TLC) by technology providers authorized under the Taxicab & Livery Passenger Enhancement Programs (TPEP/LPEP)

There are lot of records with trip duration as zero. Also, the pickup and drop off points are different with zero trip distance for those records which should be removed from the dataset

In Summary, these are the changes that needs to be done to the data before analyzing:

  1. Remove the records with negative values for any of the features
  2. Remove the records which have a total_amount recorded with trip distance as zero and same pick-up, drop-off location
  3. Calculate Trip duration (Drop-off time - Pickup time) and remove the records with different pickup, drop off location and trip duration as zero
  4. Remove the data which contains pick-up datetime or drop-off datetime with year value other than 2017
  5. Remove the records with passenger count as zero
  6. Add Month, Day of week and Hour for calculating more insights into the data
  7. Add Pick-up and Drop-off zone according to the LocationID which helps in calculating the busiest borough in NYC
  8. Add tip rate which helps in finding the area where the highest tipping customers board

Find number of rides per hour on each day based on hour¶

In [84]:
Image(filename='RideCountPerHour_Day.PNG')
Out[84]:

If the driver needs to get more number of rides, we need to aim for peak hours.

According to the above plot, the following insights can be drawn:

  1. Peak hours vary from weekdays to weekends
  2. On Weekdays, peak hours are between 7am - 9am and 5pm - 9pm. In the morning, the rides start increasing from 7am and it goes to peak at 8am and the number of rides start decreasing after 8am. In the evening, the peak hours are between 6pm - 8pm and again it goes to peak at 9pm
  3. Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday follow similar pattern. Thursday and Friday has a little different pattern compared to other weekdays.
  4. On Thurday and Friday, 12am - 2am rides are high and also the peak hour rides are more compared to other weekdays which makes them the highest earning days..
  5. When it comes to weekend, 12am - 2am are the peak hours in the morning. 12pm - 1pm and 6pm - 7pm has a good amount of rides

We have to consider one case while driving in peak hours. If the trip duration is very long in Peak hours, the driver is not going to earn profit. Driver gets profit with more short rides because every ride has a minimum fee that has to be paid by customer and surcharges can also be earned if it's a peak hour.

So, we need to find out if the driver has the possibility to drive more short rides in peak hours when compared to short or long rides rest of the day.

In [85]:
Image(filename='RideCount_TripDurPerHour.PNG')
Out[85]:

I have plotted number of rides, median of trip duration (minutes) per each pickup hour and Pickup day. I considered median because median gives the accurate center value even when there are any outliers. The orange bar is Trip duration in minutes with values on the left axis and blue bar is Ride count with values on right axis.

As Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday has similar pattern I would like to compare them first. Trip duration is high between 10am - 5pm which does not fall under peak hours considered before. During the peak hours, the duration is around 10 minutes which is not bad. There are short duration trips less than 9 minutes around 5am - 6am but the number of rides recorded are less.

The trip duration for Thursday and Friday have similar pattern with other weekdays. So, I think driving during the peak hours would make some profit for the driver.

In the weekends, the trip durations are a bit less compared to weekdays but it follows the same pattern as weekdays. It is above 10 minutes during 12am - 1am and 12pm - 5pm.

So, it's better to drive around 12am - 2am, 12pm - 1pm and 6pm - 7pm

Linear Optimization:¶

I am going to use Linear Optimization to solve this problem. Linear Programming, also called linear optimization, involves maximizing or minimizing a linear objective function, subject to a set of linear inequality or equality constraints

As we need to maximize the income, our problem is to maximize the linear objective function. Hence, we need to create the below model:

Objective: Maximize the taxi driver income

LP Form: Maximization

Decision Variables: I have considered rides as decision variables. Based on these rides, I would like to find the top combination of rides

Constrains: Number of hours spent per week should be not more than 10

Create the Linear programming Problem using Pulp¶

In [39]:
prob = pulp.LpProblem('MaximizeIncome', pulp.LpMaximize)

Create Decision variables¶

In [40]:
decision_variables = []
for rownum, row in df.iterrows():
    variable = str('x' + str(row['index']))
    variable = pulp.LpVariable(str(variable), lowBound = 0, upBound = 1, cat= 'Integer') #binary variables
    decision_variables.append(variable)

print ("Total number of decision_variables: " + str(len(decision_variables)))

Total number of decision_variables: 9632149

Define Objective Function: Maximizing the Income by maximizing the total_amount¶

In [41]:
total_cost = ""
for rownum, row in df.iterrows():
    formula = row['total_amount']*decision_variables[rownum]
    total_cost += formula

prob += total_cost

Define Constraints: The number of hours spent per week should not be greater than 10¶

In [42]:
num_hours = 10
total_hours = ""
for rownum, row in df.iterrows():
    formula = row['trip_duration']*decision_variables[rownum]
    total_hours += formula

#As the trip_duration is seconds in the dataset, convert hours to seconds
hours_tosec = num_hours*3600
prob += (total_hours == hours_tosec)
In [43]:
prob.writeLP("MaximizeIncome.lp" )

Solve the Problem using GLPK solver and find the status¶

In [44]:
prob.solve(GLPK_CMD(path = r"C:\Users\navee\AppData\Local\Continuum\anaconda3\Lib\site-packages\pulp\solverdir\glpk-4.65\w64\glpsol.exe"))

print("Status:", LpStatus[prob.status])
print("Optimal Solution to the problem: ", value(prob.objective))

The problem is solved and optimal solution is obtained. Now, get all the variables from problem to check the decision variable

If value of variable is 1 (among binary values 0 and 1), then store the index in set

In [86]:
index_name = set()

for v in prob.variables():
    if v.varValue == 1:
        st = v.name
        index_name.add(int(st[len('x'):]))

Create a column decision and update the value with 0 or 1 based on the index

In [87]:
for row in df.itertuples():
    if (row.Index in index_name):
        df.at[row.Index, 'decision'] = 1
    else:
        df.at[row.Index, 'decision'] = 0

Summary¶

In Summary, we can conclude that linear optimization produced the maximized result with combination of different rides on each day upto 10 hours. Among them, the highlights were:

  1. Friday has the highest number of rides followed by Sunday, Thursday, Monday, Saturday, Wednesday and Tuesday
  2. All weekdays has peak hour at 4pm in the evening. Thursday and Friday also has peak hours at 12 am. On Saturday, lot of rides are recorded at 12am, 3am and 12pm - 4pm On Sunday, the peak hours are at 5pm
  3. Most busiest routes are Manhattan -> Manhattan, Unknown -> Unknown, Queens -> Queens
  4. Queens has the highest tip rate which is followed by Queens
